  <!-- MB/s vs MiB/s -->
  <article class="premium-card mt-8">
    <div class="premium-card-inner">
      <h2 class="font-bold text-2xl text-gray-900 mb-6">MB/s vs MiB/s: Why Windows Makes Your Downloads Look Slower</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        There's a subtle trap in this conversion. The official decimal megabyte (<strong>MB</strong>) is 1,000,000 bytes, but many applications — including Windows file dialogs and some download tools — count in binary mebibytes (<strong>MiB</strong> = 1,048,576 bytes) while still printing "MB". The difference is about 4.9%.
      </p>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
        <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-50 to-white border border-teal-100">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">100 Mbps in decimal (SI)</h3>
          <p class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-teal-600 mb-1">12.5 MB/s</p>
          <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm">What the math says, and what ISPs and speed tests mean.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-50 to-white border border-amber-100">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">100 Mbps in binary (IEC)</h3>
          <p class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-amber-600 mb-1">11.92 MiB/s</p>
          <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm">What a MiB-counting app displays — same speed, smaller-looking number.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
        So if your 100 Mbps connection "only" shows 11.9 in a download tool, nothing is wrong — the tool is counting in binary units. Flip the calculator above to <strong>MiB/s (IEC)</strong> to match what your app displays, or read our <a href="/methodology/" class="text-indigo-600 hover:underline font-medium">calculation methodology</a> for the exact factors we use.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Why the confusion exists -->
  <article class="premium-card mt-8">
    <div class="premium-card-inner">
      <h2 class="font-bold text-2xl text-gray-900 mb-6">Why Two Units Exist at All</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Telecommunications has measured transmission in <strong>bits per second</strong> since the telegraph era — a wire carries one bit at a time, so bits are the natural unit for a data <em>stream</em>. Computer storage grew up separately around the <strong>byte</strong>, because one byte encodes one character, making it the natural unit for <em>files</em>.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Your internet connection sits exactly at the boundary: the network side (your ISP, router, and speed test) speaks bits, while the file side (your browser, OS, and downloads) speaks bytes. The confusion isn't a scam — but ISPs certainly don't mind that "100 Mbps" reads as a bigger number than "12.5 MB/s".
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
        The takeaway: any time a speed looks 8× too slow, check the unit before blaming your provider. If it looks ~5% too slow on top of that, check for MiB labeling — and if it's more than ~15% below the converted number on a wired connection, that's when something is actually wrong.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

